<article id="node-17027">
<h1 >3.4.10.40 RASF - Assessment under the Sugarcane Farmers&#039; Income Test</h1>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> THIS SCHEME CLOSED on 12 July 2007 and the following INFORMATION is FOR HISTORICAL PURPOSES ONLY.</p>
<h2>Summary</h2>
<p>This topic explains how the farmer's income is assessed for the farmers' income test (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/f/120">1.1.F.120</a>).</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../guide-social-security-law/3/4/10/30">3.4.10.30</a> RASF - Sugarcane Farmers' Income Test</p>
</div>
<h2>Assessment of income</h2>
<p>The following table explains the application of the sugarcane farmers' income test in different circumstances:</p>
<table><thead><tr><th scope="col">Example No.</th>
<th scope="col">If a qualifying farmer…</th>
<th scope="col">Then the…</th>
</tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td>
<td>was partnered at the time of divestment,</td>
<td>income of both the farmer and the partner for the previous 3 financial years is compared to the partnered Maximum Basic Entitlement.</td>
</tr><tr><td>2</td>
<td>was partnered at any time in the 3 full financial years prior to divestment, but is no longer partnered,</td>
<td>income of the farmer only (do not include partner's income) for the previous 3 financial years is compared to the partnered Maximum Basic Entitlement.</td>
</tr><tr><td>3</td>
<td>has become a member of a couple after giving the farm to the younger generation,</td>
<td>income of the farmer only is compared to the single Maximum Basic Entitlement. Income of the new spouse is NOT included in any calculations relating to the farmers' income test.</td>
</tr><tr><td>4</td>
<td>is separated due to ill health at the time of divestment,</td>
<td>applicable rate under the farmers' income test will be twice the single Maximum Basic Entitlement. Income and assets will still be assessed as for a member of a couple.</td>
</tr></tbody></table><div class="example">
<p><strong>Example 1:</strong> A widowed farmer remarried in March 2003 and in March 2005 wishes to give the sugarcane farm to his daughter and her husband, so that he and his new wife can retire. As he is a member of a couple at the time he gives the farm to his daughter, both his and his new spouse's income (including any income earned by her prior to them being married) will be assessed in the 3 financial years prior to divestment. They will be able to have combined income up to the Maximum Basic Entitlement for a partnered person.</p>
</div>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example 2:</strong> A farmer died in 2003, leaving the sugarcane farm to his widow. She gave the farm to her children in 2005, and applies for <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#age" title="Age pension">Age</a> under <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#rasf" title="Retirement assistance for sugarcane farmers scheme">RASF</a>. Although she was not a member of a couple at the time she gave the farm to her children, she was a member of a couple within the last 3 completed financial years. Her income alone, not including any income her husband received before he died, will be assessed against the Maximum Basic Entitlement for a partnered person.</p>
</div>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example 3:</strong> A farmer who was widowed in 1997 gave her farm to her son in 2005 and married her new partner in 2006. The single farmers' income test is used and only the retiring farmer's income in the 3 financial years before divestment is relevant.</p>
</div>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example 4:</strong> The husband is in a nursing home and the wife still runs the farm with their children. The applicable rate under the sugarcane farmer's income test will be twice the single maximum basic entitlement.</p>
</div>
<p>Income is generally assessed under the provisions for ordinary income (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/o/30">1.1.O.30</a>) and business structures, trusts and primary producers (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/p/389">1.1.P.389</a>).</p>
<h2>Gifts</h2>
<p>When working out income for the sugarcane farmers' income test, gifts made by the farmer or their partner (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/p/85">1.1.P.85</a>) are not subject to the deeming provisions. The deeming provisions may catch gifts that do not form part of the gifted farming assets under RASF once the person is granted Age.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 1123 Disposal of Assets</p>
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../guide-social-security-law/3/4/10/120">3.4.10.120</a> Start Date for Payments Accessed via RASF, <a href="../guide-social-security-law/4/3">4.3</a> Ordinary Income, <a href="../guide-social-security-law/4/7">4.7</a> Business Structures, Primary Production &amp; pre-01/01/2002 Assessment of Trusts &amp; Private Companies</p>
</div>
